aelienydd, Radnorshire, Wales":"Maelienydd, Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Drwsddaugoed, Llanrug, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Llanrug, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howel","type":"FIRST","meanings":["The English form of the Welsh name Hywel."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Madog","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, possibly having the sense ‘fortunate’ or alternatively from Celtic <i>aodh</i> ‘fire’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lleyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Aleksandr, Boris, Gennady, Grigory, Maryana, Mikhail, Svetlana, Veniamin, Yelena, Yeva.  Jewish Arie, Mendel, Yakov.  Dutch Dirk, Cornelis.  German Florian, Hans, Otto.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Klein  .","Dutch: variant, mainly archaic, Flemish, or Americanized, of <b>Kleijn</b>, itself a variant of   Klein  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Klein","meanings":["German, Flemish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic); Dutch (also <b>De Klein</b>): from Middle High German, German, Dutch <i>klein</i> ‘small’, or Yiddish <i>kleyn</i>. This was a nickname for a person of small stature, but is also often found as a distinguishing name for a junior male, usually a son, in German names such as   Kleinhans   and   Kleinpeter  . The surname of German origin is also found in many other European countries, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Belgium, Poland, Hungary, Czechia, and Slovakia. It is often a German translation of corresponding Slavic surnames, for example Czech and Slovak <b>Malý</b> (see   Maly  ). Compare   Klain  ,   Klien  , and   Kline  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Howel ap Madog of Lleyn was born in 1315, in Lleyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Prince Madog Of Wales, was 58 and his mother, Arddun verch Celynin of Celynin, was 56. He had at least 1 son with Lowry Verch Ap Evan."},"et":{"1315–":"1315–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1523–Male":"1523–Surnud","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1315":"1315","       1523":"1523","1523":"1523","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1256":"1256","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Lleyn, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Lleyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Maelienydd, Radnorshire, Wales":"Maelienydd, Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Drwsddaugoed, Llanrug, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Llanrug, Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1315–":"1315–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1523–Male":"1523–Kuollut","1344–Male":"1344–Kuollut","1345–Male":"1345–Kuollut","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1315":"1315","       1523":"1523","1523":"1523","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1256":"1256","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Lleyn, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Lleyn, Caernarfonshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Maelienydd, Radnorshire, Wales":"Maelienydd, Radnorshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Drwsddaugoed, Llanrug, Caernarvonshire, Wales":"Llanrug, Caernarfonshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1315–":"1315–Décédé","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1315–Male":"1315–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1523–Male":"1523–Décédé","1344–Male":"1344–Décédé","1345–Male":"1345–Décédé","1256–Male":"1256–Décédé","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1315":"1315","       1523":"1523","1523":"1523","1345":"1345","1344":"1344","1256":"1256","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Lleyn, Caernarvon